This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's exam, we can derive that languages are listed above, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a high score.
Data collected from 74 schools associated with SCIS show that 72 per cent of students received a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German students, 69 per cent of French students and 63 per cent of Spanish students also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as professionally as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A survey by the British Commission for Employment and Vocational Training in 2014 revealed that 17 per cent of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language knowledge, according to employers.
Thus, language skills are becoming more and more important to prepare young people for their future career.
Now that more and more vacancies require language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, when he has learned a second language, he will have a real benefit in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over competition.
According to a YouTube score of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. France was the only language that stood out above 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Several languages can speak, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach themselves.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are involved in providing a learning environment that prepares children and provides them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
At the moment it cannot be denied that languages remain of vital importance in a global business environment for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
